\[
\text{The singlet at 11.5 ppm corresponds to the acidic proton of the –COOH group.}
\]

\[
\text{Each compound would have a different fragmentation pattern, especially around m/z = 31 (CH}_2\text{OH}^+)\text{ for alcohol and m/z = 43 (CH}_3\text{CO}^+)\text{ for ketone.}
\]

\[
\text{A medium peak around 1640–1680 cm}^{-1}\text{ indicates the presence of a C=C bond in an alkene.}
\]

\[
\text{Yes, the molecular ion peak at m/z = 56 would confirm the molecular formula C}_4\text{H}_8.}
\]

\[
\text{IR peaks between 1450 and 1600 cm}^{-1}\text{ are characteristic of C=C bonds in aromatic rings.}
\]

\[
\text{A singlet at 7.3 ppm is typical of hydrogen atoms on a symmetrical aromatic ring, such as benzene.}
\]

\[
\text{A molecular ion peak at m/z = 78 confirms the molar mass of C}_6\text{H}_6, supporting identification as benzene.}
\]

\[
\text{The triplet suggests a CH}_3\text{ group next to a CH}_2\text{ group.}
\]

\[
\text{The quartet suggests a CH}_2\text{ group next to a CH}_3\text{ group.}
\]

\[
\text{The broad singlet is from an -OH proton typical of alcohols.}
\]

\[
\text{Triplet + quartet + OH singlet match the pattern of propan-1-ol (CH}_3\text{CH}_2\text{CH}_2\text{OH).}
\]

\[
\text{Retention time is the time a compound takes to pass through the column and be detected.}
\]

\[
\text{The peak at 1.2 minutes, since it elutes the fastest.}
\]

\[
\text{If the mobile phase becomes more polar, polar compounds elute faster and retention times decrease.}
\]

\[
\text{The peak at m/z = 46 is the molecular ion, indicating the molar mass of the whole molecule (C}_2\text{H}_6\text{O).}
\]

\[
\text{The base peak at m/z = 31 corresponds to a CH}_2\text{OH}^+\text{ fragment, common for ethanol.}
\]
